Zelda Fitzgerald was an American novelist, socialite, and the wife of F. Scott Fitzgerald. Her life and writings, although not as widely known as her husband's, offer a fascinating glimpse into the Jazz Age. Here is a collection of quotes from Zelda Fitzgerald, including her novel *Save Me the Waltz*, letters, and other writings:

---

### **From *Save Me the Waltz* (1932)**
1. "Nobody has ever measured, not even poets, how much the heart can hold."
2. "I don't want to live—I want to love first, and live incidentally."
3. "She refused to be bored chiefly because she wasn't boring."
4. "There is no disappointment so numbing...as someone no better than you achieving more."
5. "The trouble with emergencies is, said the Duchess, that I always put on my finest silk stockings and pull a limb through them."
6. "I am really only myself when I’m somebody else whom I have endowed with these wonderful qualities from my imagination."
7. "You can take off your hats now, gentlemen, and I think perhaps you'd better."
8. "The idea that to make a man work you've got to hold gold in front of his eyes is an American tradition."
9. "Nobody has anything to look back on, and there is nothing to look forward to."
10. "She knew that there was no way to keep the pain in one place—until it ate her alive."

### **On Life and Love**
11. "Living has taught me that love does not consist in gazing at each other, but in looking outward together in the same direction."
12. "I don't suppose you can have pain without beauty."
13. "Youth doesn't need friends—it only needs crowds."
14. "I'm really only myself when I'm somebody else, and the tragedy is that I can't stand myself as anybody but somebody else."
15. "I have tried to imagine what the world would be like without love, and I have found it impossible."
16. "The world can forgive practically anything except people who mind their own business."
17. "Love has no age, no limit; and no death."
18. "We grew up founding our dreams on the infinite promise of American advertising."
19. "Love is the difficult realization that something other than oneself is real."
20. "Life starts all over again when it gets crisp in the fall."

### **On Creativity and Writing**
21. "There are so many things to write, and all of them are so far from what people care about."
22. "The only answer to everything, always, is to write."
23. "I had started to write, to keep a record, to make a story, to preserve something from the time when I had been young and beautiful."
24. "Writing is always so much harder than speaking—it takes more courage and more honesty."
25. "Words are both a form of expression and a way of hiding."
26. "When writing a novel, a writer should create living people; people, not characters. A character is a caricature."
27. "My writing is a mode of expression, of coping, of saying things I cannot say out loud."
28. "All I want to be is very young always and very irresponsible and to feel that my life is my own."
29. "Writers aren't people exactly. Or, if they're any good, they're a whole lot of people trying so hard to be one person."
30. "One must never pretend that one doesn't have an imagination."

### **On Identity and Self-Discovery**
31. "She was conscious that the things she wanted had nothing to do with the things she had."
32. "I often feel that my whole life is a terrifying figure on a tightrope, careening from one impossible situation to another."
33. "I am the kind of woman who likes to look forward rather than back."
34. "I feel that I am lost, that I am not myself—this isn’t my life."
35. "Being a person is terribly difficult and tiresome."
36. "There are always ways of escaping into things more important than one's self."
37. "I hope I can be a good person without having to try to be one."
38. "I have a horror of having to be somebody else."
39. "Identity is not just about the self, but about how the self relates to the world."
40. "We are not what we think we are, but what we do."

### **On Fame and Public Image**
41. "I suppose I’ll have to accept that being the wife of a famous man is one of the crosses you bear."
42. "Being famous is quite a frailty in itself."
43. "Fame is a fickle mistress; what she gives with one hand, she takes away with the other."
44. "I often wonder whether the future is just a ploy to distract us from the present."
45. "In my opinion, the most dangerous thing about fame is that it gives people the illusion of importance."
46. "Fame isolates you from everyone, except from the people who want something from you."
47. "I am too fond of reading biographies to believe that the truth about people is interesting."
48. "Being a public figure is like being a public building—everybody thinks they own a piece of you."
49. "What good is fame if it makes you a stranger in your own life?"
50. "The fame that came with my husband’s success has often seemed more like a burden than a blessing."

### **On Art and Aesthetics**
51. "Art is not something you understand; it is something you experience."
52. "The artist's job is not to succumb to despair, but to find an antidote for the emptiness of existence."
53. "Art must be an expression of love or it is nothing."
54. "What is art but a way of seeing?"
55. "Artists are people driven by the tension between the desire to communicate and the desire to hide."
56. "Art is the only way to run away without leaving home."
57. "Art is the lie that enables us to realize the truth."
58. "Art is a collaboration between God and the artist, and the less the artist does, the better."
59. "A work of art is above all an adventure of the mind."
60. "The most beautiful thing we can experience is the mysterious; it is the source of all true art and science."

### **On Tragedy and Suffering**
61. "Tragedy is a tool for the living to gain wisdom, not a guide by which to live."
62. "Suffering becomes beautiful when anyone bears great calamities with cheerfulness."
63. "What is the use of suffering, if it does not teach us anything?"
64. "Out of suffering have emerged the strongest souls; the most massive characters are seared with scars."
65. "To suffer without complaint is the only lesson we have to learn in this life."
66. "Suffering is one very long moment. We cannot divide it by seasons."
67. "The deeper that sorrow carves into your being, the more joy you can contain."
68. "Suffering is but another name for the teaching of experience."
69. "There is no despair so absolute as that which comes with the first moments of our first great sorrow."
70. "Tragedy is the inevitable side effect of a passionate life."

### **On Gender and Social Roles**
71. "Women still remember the first kiss after men have forgotten the last."
72. "A woman knows instinctively what is true, even if she doesn’t always know what it means."
73. "I want to be something more than just a wife."
74. "The world belongs to those who do something extraordinary, and that does not necessarily include being someone’s wife."
75. "A woman without a man is like a fish without a bicycle."
76. "The greatest prison people live in is the fear of what other people think."
77. "There is no gate, no lock, no bolt that you can set upon the freedom of my mind."
78. "A woman’s life can often be a series of compromises with destiny."
79. "Men have their desires; women have their dreams."
80. "A woman is like a teabag—you never know how strong she is until she gets in hot water."

### **On the Jazz Age and Society**
81. "The parties were bigger, the pace was faster, the buildings were higher, the morals were looser."
82. "The Jazz Age is something that had to be experienced to be understood."
83. "It was an age of miracles, it was an age of art, it was an age of excess, and it was an age of satire."
84. "It was a bright, sunny day with the sun shining like a gleaming orange ball in the sky, and I wondered if the Jazz Age was really as bright as it seemed."
85. "We were the great American youth; we lived life as if it were a dance, and every step took us closer to some imaginary pinnacle of happiness."
86. "The Jazz Age was more than just a time—it was an attitude."
87. "We had fun in those days, but it was a kind of desperate fun, the kind you have when you know it can’t last."
88. "There was something about the Jazz Age that made people feel alive in a way they never had before."
89. "The Jazz Age was a time of contradictions, of wealth and poverty, of glamour and despair."
90. "The Jazz Age was a period of transgression, a time when the world seemed to lose its moral compass."

### **On Memory and the Past**
91. "Memory is a way of holding onto the things you love, the things you are, the things you never want to lose

."
92. "The past is never really past, it’s always present in our lives."
93. "Memory can be a burden, but it can also be a source of strength."
94. "The past is a place where I can go to escape the present."
95. "Our memories are the only paradise from which we can never be expelled."
96. "Time heals all wounds, but it doesn’t erase the scars."
97. "The past is a foreign country; they do things differently there."
98. "What’s the use of a good memory if you don’t know how to forget?"
99. "Nostalgia is a seductive liar."
100. "The past is never dead. It’s not even past."

---

These quotes encompass Zelda Fitzgerald's thoughts and expressions across various themes, including love, creativity, identity, and the Jazz Age. They highlight her unique voice as an artist and a thinker of her time.
